October 23, 2023
The Best Underground Sandwich Shop, and How It Came To Be
If you enjoy a history lesson and a big, delicious sandwich this blog is for you.
Walking down the whimsical underground staircase you are escorted towards the smell
of freshly baked Italian bread. When following the hidden staircase, you are led towards
an antique, large, brown door, and you discover yourself staring at a big neon red sign
that flashes Rathskeller. This is a sandwich shop that offers Boar Head deli meats and a
large variety of rolls along with a few select salads and tons of beverages offered
including select Starbucks coffee. Not to mention the homemade cookies that will make
your mouth water.
Rathskeller is a German style term that means a beer hall or restaurant in a basement or
cellar. It is a cozy and social gathering place where people are meant to enjoy drinks,
food and good company. The word rathskeller is derived from the German words
rathaus meaning town hall and keller meaning cellar. Nick named The Rat, by
college students. Today they are not as common as they once were but can still be found
in certain locations like universities, historical buildings, and traditional German
establishments. This Rathskeller specifically, is located at 401 W Kennedy Blvd, Tampa
Florida.
This is one of the most popular dining options, which is called the Rathskeller. At the
University of Tampa campus, we have a multitude of dining options ranging from the
Ultimate dining hall, Salsa Rico, Star Ginger, AFC Sushi and more. Rathskeller easily tops
the list, no questions asked.
Rathskeller is located approximately 4 feet underground. Established in 1963, the
building is entered down a set of stairs underneath the Henry B Plant Museum. Around
the turn of the century, gentlemen vacationing at the Tampa Bay Hotel could enjoy a
game of pool, have a drink or get a haircut at the Rathskeller. There was even a separate
cafe for women.
Unfortunately, the bar, haircutter, pool games, and caf have since been retired. Almost
100 years after Henry B. Plant built his Tampa Bay Hotel and installed a bar in the
basement, the Rathskeller continues to be a hit, just for different occasions. Now a part
of the University of Tampa's Plant Hall, the Rat is popular among students, faculty, staff
and a growing sector of the public, and museum visitors.
The building has undergone renovations and upgrades including new furniture and light
fixtures, but the walls are still covered with historical artifacts, pictures and stories to
enjoy. Whenever I have a group assignment or project to complete, I always try my
hardest to convince my peers to work on it in the Rat. It is most times quiet and empty,
plus we can bond over food, and believe it or not but I think the Ratskeller has one of the
strongest Wi-Fi connections on the entire campus, it is ironic. said Victoria Ochs, a
sophomore at the University of Tampa. As states the spaces are used for much more
than just creating and devouring a sandwich. Students use the room to relax, study,
catch up with friends, lounge, do group activities, or even meet with professors.
There is no better way to hide from the 100-degree sun outside than in the Rathskeller,
not to mention it is the most pleasurable dining option offered on campus is easy. Its a
win win says sophomore, Campbell Jameson at The University of Tampa. She isnt
wrong, served up by some of the Universities friendliest staff, I always go for a six-inch
Italian sandwich, which includes Boars Head provolone cheese, ham, salami, chipotle
mayo, the Sub way styled deli lets you choose from a variety of different fresh vegetable
toppings, spices, and oils. My go to toppings consist of lettuce, tomato, banana peppers,
crunchy pickles, and vinegar, oil, and Italian spices. They also have a preselected
favorites styled menu including the renegade, the bistro, the spartan, and even tuna and
chicken salad. Boars Head deli meat is known for its high quality and delicious taste.
They use premium ingredients and traditional recipes, their commitment to
craftsmanship sets them apart and makes their products stand out of the crowd.
The place does not compare to Jersey Mikes, Subway, Wawa, Jimmy Johns at all, they
have some of the most garden-fresh produce and natural pre sliced lunch meats, you can
tell this place means business. Hands down BEST place to eat on the University of
Tampa campus. Im a senior and only discovered this place last semester but Im grateful
every day that I did. The Boars meat is great, and the veggies and spreads are fresh. My
favorite spread is chipotle mayo. Its spicy and adds amazing flavor to your sandwich. If
you eat here, you have to start with the signature Rathskeller sandwich! Make sure to
get the Italian bread too. Oh, so good. They usually pack lots of veggies in there, so I
dont feel guilty said Gracie Galan, senior, at UT.
Rathskeller is not only for the students, but also open for the public to enjoy and
experience as well. Henry B. Plant Museum tours bring you down into the history of the
Rathskeller as well, specially trained docents will guide your party of ten or more on a
one-hour tour through the Museum. This is a great outing for civic organizations,
retirement communities, business trips, and other group activities. For docent led groups
tours of 10 or more, the price is $14 for adults and $12 for seniors. Guided tours are
available from January to October.
It is open from 10am- 3pm, Monday through Friday, but good luck trying to avoid the
line, because speaking from experience I have learned it is near to impossible, which is a
perfect representation of how good this place really is. Half a sandwich is $6.99 and a
whole 12 inch is $9.49. You can also get a meal which includes two bags of chips and a
fountain drink for $12.99. Rathskeller accepts students Spartans dollars or credit cards
as a form or payment, tragically they do not accept the UT meal swipe plan. Not only is
this a great place to sit, stay, and eat, but a perfect, quick, easy on the go solution for
when there is not enough time for other more complex dining solutions or if you prefer
to sit in the fresh air.
Great food, cheap prices, and an awesome atmosphere, how can you beat it?
One thing that could make the Rathskeller even better is bringing the bar back to life.
Students would take full advantage of having a bar on campus, which makes it safe for
students having no need to drive. The bar never reopened after renovations and there
has been no reason why it has stayed off limits. The bar reopening would be legendary,
it would be the perfect spot to meet new friends, create bonds, and host events for frats
and sororities. I wish I went to college here when the bar was open so I could experience
it myself senior, Maya Critchfield at The University of Tampa said. Not to mention how
the alumni classes always enjoyed reuniting and coming back to carve their name into
the bar that helped them survive through college.
Along with bringing back the bar students say, I love the Boars head sandwiches but
one thing that would make this sandwich superior above all, would be if we were able to
get them toasted, I think it would make the sandwich just THAT much better said,
sophomore, Ryleigh Wrenker at The University of Tampa. As unique as the Rathskeller
may be students still have suggestions to make it even more superior to fit their
futuristic lifestyle.
Sandwiches are good for the soul. They are a major comfort food that are packed with
delicious flavors that suit our cravings and bring happiness. The best part is they are
customizable to suit our individual tastes or cravings so everyone can be pleased.
Sandwiches have a special way of satisfying our stomachs, warming our hearts and filling
our souls with happiness. Serving up sandwiches with a side of history. After reading this
I hope you are highly influenced and convinced that Rathskeller is worth the time,
money, and effort to check out if you are in the Tampa Bay area. The place where you
can feed your brain history and your stomach delightfulness.
Key words- University of Tampa food, underground sandwiches, rathskeller, best food
on campus, underneath plant hall, bar on UT campus
